1. When the two endpoints are equal, you should return `end`, not two times that.
2. When `start &gt; end`, you should also increment `end` in the recursive call since you&#39;re adding `end` to the result.

```java
public static int sumInt(int start, int end) {
    if (start == end) {
        return end;
    }
    else if (start &lt; end){
        return start + sumInt(start + 1, end);
    }
    else if (start &gt; end) {
        return end + sumInt (end + 1, start);
    }
    return 0;
}
```

This can be simplified using `Math.min` and `Math.max` to reduce casework:

```java
public static int sumInt(int start, int end) {
    if (start == end) return end;
    int first = Math.min(start, end);
    return first + sumInt(first + 1, Math.max(start, end));
}
```

To simplify the code (imho) and still make it recursive, I would employ a helper method.
- `sumInt()` simply calls the helper with the arguments reversed if required.
- `sumIntHelper()` actually computes the recursive sum.
```
System.out.println(sumInt(2, 7));
System.out.println(sumInt(7, 2));
System.out.println(sumInt(12, 12));
    

public static int sumInt(int start, int end) {
    return start &gt; end ? sumIntHelper(end, start)
            : sumIntHelper(start, end);
}

private static int sumIntHelper(int start, int end) {
    if (start+1 &lt; end) {
        return start + sumIntHelper(start + 1, end);
    }
    return start + end;
}
```
